There's another game.

00:04:36.650 --> 00:04:38.358
It might be a little
bit more US-centric.

00:04:38.358 --> 00:04:41.810
It's called Family Guy
Quest for Stuff and TinyCo.

00:04:41.810 --> 00:04:42.510
Hands?

00:04:42.510 --> 00:04:43.230
A couple of you.

00:04:43.230 --> 00:04:43.730
Love it.

00:04:43.730 --> 00:04:43.990
No.

00:04:43.990 --> 00:04:44.560
Few of you.

00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:45.059
I love it.

00:04:45.059 --> 00:04:45.627
OK.

00:04:45.627 --> 00:04:47.460
And the last one is
going to be Hearthstone.

00:04:47.460 --> 00:04:49.200
Who's played that
game from Blizzard?

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:49.700
Yeah.

00:04:49.700 --> 00:04:50.199
OK.

00:04:50.199 --> 00:04:51.711
About the same
number as Two Dots.

00:04:51.711 --> 00:04:52.210
Fantastic.

00:04:52.210 --> 00:04:53.856
These three games are amazing.

00:04:53.856 --> 00:04:55.230
They're all very,
very different.

00:04:55.230 --> 00:04:57.600
Two Dots is pretty much
as casual of a game

00:04:57.600 --> 00:04:59.000
as you can get.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:00.990
TinyCo is Family Guy's
kind of a builder, very

00:05:00.990 --> 00:05:03.610
much like a SimCity game, kind
of in that mid-core range.

00:05:03.610 --> 00:05:05.636
And Hearthstone is
almost as core of a game

00:05:05.636 --> 00:05:06.760
as you see on the platform.

00:05:06.760 --> 00:05:09.270
So tried to pick three very,
very different games and game

00:05:09.270 --> 00:05:12.005
design, style, genre
across the board.

00:05:12.005 --> 00:05:14.380
So let's talk about these
games and how they're designed.

00:05:17.750 --> 00:05:19.542
This is Family Guy
Quest for Stuff.

00:05:19.542 --> 00:05:21.000
I found this image
on the internet,

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.870
because it's quite descriptive
of how this game has

00:05:25.870 --> 00:05:27.320
been engaging for so long.

00:05:27.320 --> 00:05:30.520
This is a year's worth
of content in the game.

00:05:30.520 --> 00:05:32.930
We're a year and a half in,
but this is exactly one year

00:05:32.930 --> 00:05:34.400
of content in the game.

00:05:34.400 --> 00:05:36.830
And the cycle for how this
game is operated and run

00:05:36.830 --> 00:05:38.220
as a service.

00:05:38.220 --> 00:05:42.435
As TinyCo releases new content,
players build the content.

00:05:42.435 --> 00:05:43.240
They experience it.

00:05:43.240 --> 00:05:44.073
It's a builder game.

00:05:44.073 --> 00:05:46.380
It's kind of like a SimCity
or game or a FarmVille

00:05:46.380 --> 00:05:47.400
or something like that.

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:48.510
Players build the content.

00:05:48.510 --> 00:05:49.968
They kind of go
through it and then

00:05:49.968 --> 00:05:52.580
they have the content
in their beautiful city.

00:05:52.580 --> 00:05:54.812
And then TinyCo
releases more content.

00:05:54.812 --> 00:05:57.270
Players experience it, build
it, and kind of go through it.

00:05:57.270 --> 00:05:59.350
And this cycle continues
on and on and on.

00:05:59.350 --> 00:06:01.960
And TinyCo kind of has
to go through this cycle

00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:03.910
very, very quickly--
every couple of weeks

00:06:03.910 --> 00:06:06.040
release new content.

00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:09.280
And I call it, not
pejoratively, because I really

00:06:09.280 --> 00:06:12.430
love these games, but I
call the content furnace.

00:06:12.430 --> 00:06:15.727
And the furnace, the
way it burns things up.

00:06:15.727 --> 00:06:17.310
The reason I call
it a content furnace

00:06:17.310 --> 00:06:21.440
is TinyCo ships this content and
then players kind of experience

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:21.940
it.

00:06:21.940 --> 00:06:22.829
They burn it up.

00:06:22.829 --> 00:06:25.120
It's just kind of like you're
putting coals in the fire

00:06:25.120 --> 00:06:26.780
just to keep the fire going.

00:06:26.780 --> 00:06:28.940
And if you were to stop
putting coals in the fire,

00:06:28.940 --> 00:06:31.149
that furnace would
kind of die off.

00:06:31.149 --> 00:06:32.690
It's one way to keep
players engaged,

00:06:32.690 --> 00:06:35.630
but it's very, very resource
intensive and very resource

00:06:35.630 --> 00:06:37.210
heavy.

00:06:37.210 --> 00:06:39.820
And in that way, the
content furnace actually

00:06:39.820 --> 00:06:41.790
doesn't scale very well.

00:06:41.790 --> 00:06:44.000
My content furnace, another
way I want to say this,

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:47.180
it's kind of just
single player content.

00:06:47.180 --> 00:06:50.150
One piece of content equals
one piece of engagement.

00:06:50.150 --> 00:06:51.900
Once you kind of
experience it, you really

00:06:51.900 --> 00:06:54.670
can't experience it again.

00:06:54.670 --> 00:06:56.580
It doesn't scale very well.

00:06:56.580 --> 00:06:58.650
So the question is,
when you're designing

00:06:58.650 --> 00:07:02.595
games for engagement-- this is
one model-- but what scales?

00:07:02.595 --> 00:07:04.220
How can you get more
bang for your buck

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:06.496
out of your development hour,
your development dollar?

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:10.910
Here we go.

00:07:10.910 --> 00:07:13.264
Let's take a look at this
example from Two Dots.

00:07:13.264 --> 00:07:14.680
Half of you have
played this game,

00:07:14.680 --> 00:07:17.210
so I don't need to explain
exactly what this game is

00:07:17.210 --> 00:07:17.870
about.

00:07:17.870 --> 00:07:20.920
But it's-- for those of you who
haven't-- it's a match game.

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:23.790
It's not unlike Candy
Crush or Cookie Jam.

00:07:23.790 --> 00:07:27.110
And matching games actually
are very much content furnaces

00:07:27.110 --> 00:07:27.930
in their own.

00:07:27.930 --> 00:07:31.670
Cookie Jam and Candy Crush each
have over a thousand levels,

00:07:31.670 --> 00:07:34.580
which is an incredible amount
of content, each meticulously

00:07:34.580 --> 00:07:35.880
designed and balanced.

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:38.590
Two Dots itself has over 400.

00:07:38.590 --> 00:07:40.900
So there is definitely
a content furnace here.

00:07:40.900 --> 00:07:41.970
They release new levels.

00:07:41.970 --> 00:07:43.436
Their most highly
engaged players

00:07:43.436 --> 00:07:45.060
will go through them
very, very quickly

00:07:45.060 --> 00:07:46.517
and then just kind
of wait around.

00:07:46.517 --> 00:07:47.100
Come on, guys.

00:07:47.100 --> 00:07:47.860
Release new levels.

00:07:47.860 --> 00:07:49.526
There's definitely
content furnace here.

00:07:49.526 --> 00:07:52.100
But the story doesn't end there.

00:07:52.100 --> 00:07:54.670
Here is the most
interesting part.

00:07:54.670 --> 00:07:57.040
So again, this is my
score on level 123.

00:07:57.040 --> 00:07:58.530
It's 242.

00:07:58.530 --> 00:08:00.520
I got one of three stars.

00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:04.490
And here's my little face
on the leaderboard here.

00:08:04.490 --> 00:08:07.030
My friend Aaron actually has
a higher score than I do.

00:08:07.030 --> 00:08:09.000
And I'm beating Eric.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:09.880
So what can I do?

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:12.320
I could go on and
play level 124,

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:14.740
continue to burn
through the content--

00:08:14.740 --> 00:08:16.562
because it's a content furnace.

00:08:16.562 --> 00:08:18.270
But the subtle thing
that's going on here

00:08:18.270 --> 00:08:22.360
is I'm being encouraged to
actually replay this level, two

00:08:22.360 --> 00:08:24.120
different ways in fact.

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:26.590
I'm encouraged to go ahead
and get a higher star

00:08:26.590 --> 00:08:28.940
rating, achieve this
higher star rating,

00:08:28.940 --> 00:08:30.304
which is set by the developer.

00:08:30.304 --> 00:08:32.470
I'm also being encouraged
to go ahead and beat Aaron

00:08:32.470 --> 00:08:34.350
and his little smiling
face, because he's

00:08:34.350 --> 00:08:36.516
kind of taunting me right
there with his high score.

00:08:39.169 --> 00:08:40.890
So chasing that
personal achievement,

00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:42.980
like a three-star
rating or trying

00:08:42.980 --> 00:08:45.110
to beat a friend's high
score, these actions

00:08:45.110 --> 00:08:50.030
actually drive repeat engagement
with the same type of content.

00:08:50.030 --> 00:08:50.980
This actually scales.

00:08:53.580 --> 00:08:57.670
And hence, in this way,
replayability of your content

00:08:57.670 --> 00:08:59.690
is what scales.

00:08:59.690 --> 00:09:02.300
This is the key message here.

00:09:02.300 --> 00:09:04.150
If you want to get more
bang for your buck,

00:09:04.150 --> 00:09:07.870
for your development dollar,
for your development hour,

00:09:07.870 --> 00:09:11.070
replayability of your
content is the key.

00:09:11.070 --> 00:09:14.720
One unit of content, instead of
equaling one unit of engagement

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:16.230
like we saw with
the TinyCo example,

00:09:16.230 --> 00:09:19.495
it equals many
units of engagement.

00:09:19.495 --> 00:09:21.370
Now we talked about, on
that previous slide--

00:09:21.370 --> 00:09:22.800
let's go back to it real quick.

00:09:22.800 --> 00:09:24.175
This achievement
here-- the three

00:09:24.175 --> 00:09:26.660
stars-- it's kind of
a limited achievement.

00:09:26.660 --> 00:09:28.212
Once I hit it, I'm
actually not going

00:09:28.212 --> 00:09:29.920
to want to try to hit
that again-- once I

00:09:29.920 --> 00:09:32.189
hit my three stars.

00:09:32.189 --> 00:09:33.230
But the leaderboard here.

00:09:33.230 --> 00:09:36.480
Let's say I do go back, and I
try to beat Aaron's high score.

00:09:36.480 --> 00:09:37.440
And I beat him.

00:09:37.440 --> 00:09:40.100
Maybe I post on
Facebook, or Twitter,

00:09:40.100 --> 00:09:43.240
or email him directly or
just run into him and say,

00:09:43.240 --> 00:09:45.070
hey, man, I beat
your high score.

00:09:45.070 --> 00:09:47.580
Well, he's probably going
to be encouraged to beat me.

00:09:47.580 --> 00:09:49.481
But maybe then Eric
gets in on the action.

00:09:49.481 --> 00:09:51.730
And this could go on back
and forth and back and forth

00:09:51.730 --> 00:09:53.800
and back and forth
for a very long time.

00:09:53.800 --> 00:09:56.160
So whereas this personal
achievement up here

00:09:56.160 --> 00:09:58.700
which is set by the developer
of getting up to three stars

00:09:58.700 --> 00:10:02.250
is something that's kind of
a limited thing, high scores,

00:10:02.250 --> 00:10:07.040
in this type of competition,
infinitely scales.

00:10:07.040 --> 00:10:08.640
So we talked about
how replayability

00:10:08.640 --> 00:10:11.700
is what actually gets
things to scale in general.

