00:18:08.010 --> 00:18:11.630
And I wish I knew which
community manager I was talking

00:18:11.630 --> 00:18:14.740
to when I heard this, but it's
really, really interesting.

00:18:14.740 --> 00:18:16.930
It's kind of a very,
very critical point.

00:18:16.930 --> 00:18:20.010
We've been talking a lot
today about getting the most

00:18:20.010 --> 00:18:23.400
out of your development
dollar, your development hour,

00:18:23.400 --> 00:18:26.020
because we're all
resource constrained.

00:18:26.020 --> 00:18:28.020
The thing about community.

00:18:28.020 --> 00:18:30.930
You can develop your
community in real-time

00:18:30.930 --> 00:18:34.390
without bothering an
engineer, without bothering

00:18:34.390 --> 00:18:36.470
an artist, without
a product manager,

00:18:36.470 --> 00:18:38.410
without going
through a QA cycle,

00:18:38.410 --> 00:18:41.430
without pushing out a
release on Google Play,

00:18:41.430 --> 00:18:43.190
without going through
a review process.

00:18:43.190 --> 00:18:46.190
You can develop your
community in parallel,

00:18:46.190 --> 00:18:49.712
in real-time as your
game is being developed.

00:18:49.712 --> 00:18:51.940
It's kind of an obvious thing.

00:18:51.940 --> 00:18:54.190
But it's also a very,
very critical thing.

00:18:54.190 --> 00:18:55.910
Your community is always on.

00:18:55.910 --> 00:18:57.150
It's always engaged.

00:18:57.150 --> 00:18:59.840
And you can always be doing
more to engage your community.

00:18:59.840 --> 00:19:01.831
And again, you
don't have to kind

00:19:01.831 --> 00:19:04.330
of work with your development
team, and kind of slot things,

00:19:04.330 --> 00:19:06.180
and kind of fight for resources.

00:19:06.180 --> 00:19:08.570
Your community manager
or your community team

00:19:08.570 --> 00:19:10.705
is completely independent.

00:19:10.705 --> 00:19:12.204
And that's a pretty
critical aspect.

00:19:14.990 --> 00:19:17.960
One last thing about community.

00:19:17.960 --> 00:19:21.640
We've talked about community
in sort of that online sense.

00:19:21.640 --> 00:19:24.905
I've shown images of Twitter
feeds and talked about YouTube

00:19:24.905 --> 00:19:25.780
and things like that.

00:19:28.580 --> 00:19:31.150
But probably the best way you
can engage with your users

00:19:31.150 --> 00:19:34.989
is in real life,
directly, one-on-one.

00:19:34.989 --> 00:19:36.530
So I want to give
the example of Glu.

00:19:36.530 --> 00:19:38.925
I've been working with Glu
for a very, very long time.

00:19:38.925 --> 00:19:42.400
And they've got two of the
biggest games on our platform,

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:44.400
Racing Rivals, which is
the number one racing

00:19:44.400 --> 00:19:47.490
game on our platform, and Kim
Kardashian Hollywood, which

00:19:47.490 --> 00:19:51.480
I'm sure you all are
very familiar with.

00:19:51.480 --> 00:19:55.850
They've done community events
which I think are quite unique

00:19:55.850 --> 00:20:00.260
and kind of display the power
of what community can really

00:20:00.260 --> 00:20:02.210
bring to the table.

00:20:02.210 --> 00:20:03.814
Let's look at Racing Rivals.

00:20:03.814 --> 00:20:06.230
Again, Racing Rivals has been
around for many, many years.

00:20:06.230 --> 00:20:08.880
It started out as a Facebook
game, and now it's on mobile.

00:20:08.880 --> 00:20:10.860
And it's got a cohort
of users that have just

00:20:10.860 --> 00:20:12.480
been playing this
game and collecting

00:20:12.480 --> 00:20:14.365
cards for many, many years.

00:20:14.365 --> 00:20:16.240
They're very, very
passionate about the game.

00:20:16.240 --> 00:20:17.140
They spent a lot of money.

00:20:17.140 --> 00:20:18.460
They're super engaged with it.

00:20:18.460 --> 00:20:20.440
They're gear heads as
people like to say.

00:20:20.440 --> 00:20:23.770
People who are really into
cars are really into this game.

00:20:23.770 --> 00:20:26.270
So the studio down
in Long Beach,

00:20:26.270 --> 00:20:28.920
as they were kind of developing
the next suite of features,

00:20:28.920 --> 00:20:31.460
they thought to themselves,
well, you know what?

00:20:31.460 --> 00:20:34.445
We've got a core group of people
involved in this game that

00:20:34.445 --> 00:20:36.320
should probably have a
little bit of input as

00:20:36.320 --> 00:20:37.740
to what we develop next.

00:20:37.740 --> 00:20:40.950
Because you look at the roadmap
of things you could develop.

00:20:40.950 --> 00:20:42.480
You could develop
it in a vacuum,

00:20:42.480 --> 00:20:45.320
or you can do what Glu did.

00:20:45.320 --> 00:20:48.180
They flew out to
Long Beach-- 20 or 25

00:20:48.180 --> 00:20:49.970
of their most highly
engaged players--

00:20:49.970 --> 00:20:52.940
and had a round table
discussion about what should we

00:20:52.940 --> 00:20:55.059
do next in Racing Rivals.

00:20:55.059 --> 00:20:56.100
And they talked about it.

00:20:56.100 --> 00:20:57.350
They kind of scoped it out.

00:20:57.350 --> 00:21:00.410
And they essentially
turned their community

00:21:00.410 --> 00:21:02.350
